ution of EDTA  (ethylenediamine-N,N,N',N'-tetraacetic acid) at 21 for periods ranging from  3 to 9 months (Borggaard, 1979, 1981). If that time period could be shortened  appreciably,-the procedure would promise to be more widely useful. It seemed  possible that extraction time might be reduced if higher temperatures were  used. Consequently, extractions of samples were conducted at temperatures  of 40C and 90C and at several pH values. Results of those experiments are  reportod in this note.    0016-7061/81/0000--0000/$02.50 1981 Elsevier Scientific Publishing Company    122    MATERIALS AND METHODS    Soils    Two soil samples were used in the experiments, one from Denmark and the  other from Tanzania. The first sample came from the surface layer of sandy  loam of a Eutric Cambisol at Hem in Jutland, Denmark; it was also used in de-  velopment of the ,,standard" method (Borggaard, 1979). The second sample  was of clay texture from the deeper part (60--90 cm) of a profile of a Ferric  Acrisol in the West Lake region of Tanzania (Merg, 1972; Borggaard, 1981).  In this paper, the first one is called the Hem sample and the second one the Bull  2A sample.    Methods    The preparation of the EDTA solutions and the extraction procedure have  been described previously (Borggaard, 1979). In the latest experiments, the  solutions were at several different pH values and extractions were made at  higher temperatures than those of the ,,standard". The extractions were carried  out in plastic bottles in a thermostatically controlled water bath with continual  shaking. At the end of the extraction period the bottles were centrifuged at  3000 g for 20 min and the supernatant filtered. Amounts of extracted iron  were determined by atomic absorption spectrophotometry.    RESULTS    The amounts of iron removed from the two samples are shown in the two  graphs in Fig. 1 as functions of extraction time. Within the graphs are given the  soil: solution ratios, the pH values of the solutions, and the temperatures. For  comparison, the amounts of iron extracted by the ,,standard" method are shown  as straight lines in the two graphs.  Selective extraction of iron oxides in amorphous form is considered to have  been achieved if two conditions are met. First, amounts of iron removed be-  come stable and do not increase significantly (95% level) after some extraction  time. Second, the amounts extracted within that time do not exceed those  removed by the ,,standard" method.  A temperature of 90 is clearly too high for extraction of amorphous iron  oxides only. For both samples, the removal of iron continued at that temper-  ature for the full time interval of the longest extractions. For sample BuII 2A  from Tanzania, results of the extraction at pH 4.9 and 90 agree with those  of Torrent et al. {1980) who found that ~he amounts removed by EDTA at  pH 4.7 5 and 90 became '.arger with increasing extraction time in an almost  linear fashion.  A temperature of 40 showed limited promise; it did allow shorter extrac-  tion times for one sample but did not work for the other. The amount of iron    123    [             HEM            ---           SOLUTION    M   r  0.15-                              40   8.8 2:50      0.i  0                          7.9  1:50  0                  90            0.1  0.10-    0                                                                            4.9   1  50  o   _      I       I       I  .    I       i                                  _.           BuI 1 2A                               0        TEMP,  pH   SOIL:    ~I]TA~             SOLUTION     M  o,8 -           O  o           A          1:1oo  0                      ~   40  9.9  2:50       0.1  o,4 E(::~]D 0    O 0     O      90  4.9  1:50     0.1  ,  AVv  0       I      I      I      I      1  l0       20       311}       140       50     DAYS (/40 C)  ,CURS (90-C)  Fig. 1. Amounts of iron extracted from the two soil samples by various EDTA solutions  at 40 and 90 