 in treatment of the Hem sample at  pH 9--10 and 40C. This inference is based on the amount of magnesium ex-  tracted. The amount equaled exchangeable magnesium and was independent  of the extraction time. By way of contrast, some of the crystalline minerals in  sample BuII 2A were apparently attacked at pH 9.9 and 40C. Such attack is  inferred from the continued removal of iron as the time interval of treatment  was increased. The susceptibility of the Tanzanian sample to attack is ascribed  to poor crystall,:nity of iron oxide minerals. Torrent et al. {1980) reported pref-  erential dissolution by EDTA of poorly crystalline hematite at pH 4.75 and  90C. Similar attacks on both hematite and goethite are believed to have oc-  curred in extractions of the sample from Tanzania.  CONCLUSIONS  Extractions ~vith EDTA at higher temperatures to shorten the time required  for selective removal of amorphous iron oyides do not seem feasible generally.  The results with t.~,e soil sample from Dem~ark suggest that a temperature of  40 might work for some soils. On the other hand, results with the sample  from Tanzania demonstra'!;e that temperatures higher than that of the ,,stan-  dard" method (21) were not suitable for other soil samples. The possibility  of reducing the time required for selective extraction of amorphous iron ox-  ides by EDTA thus seem doubtful at best.  ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS  My thanks are due to Dr. J. P. MCberg for providing and classifying the  Tanzanian soil sample, to H. E. M. Christensen for carrying out most of the  chemical analyses, and to the Danish Agricultural and Veterinary Research  Council for financial support.  REFERENCES  Borggaard, O. K., 1979. Selective extraction of amorphous iron oxides by EDTA from a  Danish sandy loam. J. Soil Sci., 30: 727--734.  Borggaard, O. K., 198:t. Selective extraction of amorphous iron oxides by EDTA from se-  lected soils from Denmark and Tanzania. J. Soil. Sci. In press.  Merg, J. P., 1972. Some soil fertility 